a-busy=3D"false" dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"--animation-duration: 400ms; --fade-a=
nimation-function: linear;"><p data-path-to-node=3D"0">Deep breaths. Git ha=
s a unique way of making even the best developers feel like they're fightin=
g a ghost in the machine. If you're seeing "branch does not exist," it usua=
lly means there is a disconnect between what your computer thinks the branc=
h is named and what the server (GitHub/GitLab) thinks.</p><p data-path-to-n=
ode=3D"1">Let=E2=80=99s quickly find out where the wires are crossed. Run t=
hese two commands and tell me what they say:</p><ol start=3D"1" data-path-t=
o-node=3D"2"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"2,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"2,0=
,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0"><code data-path-to-node=3D"2,0,0" data-index-i=
n-node=3D"0">git branch</code></b> (This shows your current local branch na=
me).</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"2,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"2,1=
,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0"><code data-path-to-node=3D"2,1,0" data-index-i=
n-node=3D"0">git remote -v</code></b> (This confirms if your local project =
is actually connected to a server).</p></li></ol><hr data-path-to-node=3D"3=
"><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"4">Three Common Fixes for "Branch Does Not Exist=
"</h3><p data-path-to-node=3D"5">If you are trying to push and it's failing=
, try one of these:</p><ul data-path-to-node=3D"6"><li><p data-path-to-node=
=3D"6,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"6,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">The "I j=
ust created this" Fix:</b>
If the branch is brand new, the server doesn't know it exists yet. Force it=
 to recognize it with:
<code data-path-to-node=3D"6,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"129">git push -u or=
igin HEAD</code>
<i data-path-to-node=3D"6,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"153">(This tells Git: =
"Take whatever branch I am on right now and push it to origin.")</i></p></l=
i><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"6,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"6,1,0" data-in=
dex-in-node=3D"0">The Case-Sensitivity Fix:</b>
Git is picky. If your branch is named <code data-path-to-node=3D"6,1,0" dat=
a-index-in-node=3D"64">Feature-Login</code> but you type <code data-path-to=
-node=3D"6,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"91">git push origin feature-login</co=
de>, it will fail. Ensure the capitalization matches <b data-path-to-node=
=3D"6,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"170">exactly</b>.</p></li><li><p data-path=
-to-node=3D"6,2,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"6,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">=
The "Main vs Master" Fix:</b>
Many older tutorials use <code data-path-to-node=3D"6,2,0" data-index-in-no=
de=3D"51">master</code>, but most new repositories use <code data-path-to-n=
ode=3D"6,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D"89">main</code>. If you tried <code dat=
a-path-to-node=3D"6,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D"108">git push origin master<=
